The unified model of AGN25 postulates that the accreting supermassive black hole is surrounded by an optically-thick torus at scales of about 1 pc. This would cause an attenuation e−τ of the flux from the AGN: the optical depth τ of the torus is null along the polar direction and it reaches a maximum of τ≃1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tau \simeq 1$$\end{document} at the equator26. Flux attenuation by the interstellar medium in the Galaxy is negligible with respect to the AGN torus because it is always optically thin and it may reach a maximum optical depth27 of only τ≃0.001\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\tau \simeq 0.001$$\end{document}. We consider that the attenuation is due to Thomson scattering in the medium.

